<DOC><DOCNO> AP890608-0277 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-06-08-89 2126EST</FILEID><FIRST>s f BC-SEC-Glance Adv11   06-08 0274</FIRST><SECOND>BC-SEC-Glance, Adv 11,0286</SECOND><HEAD>$adv11</HEAD><HEAD>Advance for release Sunday, June 11</HEAD><HEAD>With BC-SEC Future</HEAD><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Here are some facts and figures about theSecurities and Exchange Commission:</TEXT><TEXT>   HISTORY: The SEC was created in 1934 as part of the SecuritiesExchange Act in a wave of financial regulation under PresidentFranklin D. Roosevelt reacting to the stock market crash of 1929 andsubsequent Depression.   DUTIES: The Washington-based commission is charged withregulating the nation's financial markets and market professionals,including all stock exchanges, brokers and investment firms. Itregulates financial disclosures by companies and enforces federalsecurities laws.   The SEC is run by a panel of five commissioners, including achairman.   It has a total staff of about 2,130, including 800 attorneys, in13 cities: Atlanta; Boston; Chicago; Denver; Fort Worth, Texas;Houston; Los Angeles; Miami; New York; Philadelphia; Salt Lake City;San Francisco; Seattle; and Washington.   The commission has the power to penalize securities-law violatorswith fines, suspensions and oversight. It can refer cases to theJustice Department for criminal prosecution.   In 1988, the SEC brought 252 enforcement actions, includinginsider trading, corporate reporting, market manipulation, fraud andother cases. It also reviewed 10,985 disclosure filings, 4,000 morethan in 1983.   FINANCING: The SEC had a budget of $142.6 million, up from $73million in 1980. It has requested $168.7 million for fiscal 1990.   In 1987, the commission raised about $264 million from stockregistration fees and $121 million from court orders to defendantsto return illicit profits. Under federal securities laws, though,the agency cannot use any of the money it raises.</TEXT><NOTE>End advance for Sunday, June 11</NOTE></DOC>